{
  "name": "kiro-recall: Auto Vault Sync",
  "version": "1.0.0",
  "description": "Fires after spec task completion. Filters for parent tasks, resolves the project name, generates a structured Capture Note, writes it to 00-inbox/, and appends a summary to the project note in 01-projects/.",
  "when": {
    "type": "postTaskExecution"
  },
  "then": {
    "type": "askAgent",
    "prompt": "You are running the kiro-recall auto vault sync hook. This hook fires after a spec task completes. Your job is to determine whether the completed task is a parent task and, if so, capture a structured note to the vault inbox.\n\n## Preamble — Check vault availability\n\nBefore doing anything else, confirm that the mcpvault MCP server is available. Attempt a lightweight mcpvault operation (for example, listing the contents of `00-inbox/`).\n\nIf mcpvault responds successfully, proceed to Step 1.\n\nIf mcpvault is unavailable, not connected, or returns a connection error, output the following message and stop immediately. Do not proceed to any further steps.\n\n> Vault sync skipped this time. The vault connection wasn't available, but no worries — your task completed just fine. The note will be captured next time the hook fires successfully.\n\nDo not output any stack traces, exception details, or internal error messages. Just the friendly message above, then stop.\n\n## Step 1 — Inspect completed task\n\nParse the task completion context provided by the postTaskExecution event.\n\nExtract the following from the context:\n- **Task description**: the text of the completed task\n- **Spec path**: the path to the spec directory (the folder containing `tasks.md`, `requirements.md`, and `design.md`)\n- **Task file path**: the path to the `tasks.md` file for this spec\n\nIf the task description or task file path cannot be determined from the context, output nothing and stop — do not proceed further.\n\n## Step 2 — Parent task filter\n\nRead `tasks.md` from the spec using the task file path extracted in Step 1.\n\nDetermine whether the completed task is a parent task or a sub-task:\n- A **parent task** is a top-level checkbox line in `tasks.md` — a line matching the pattern `- [ ] N. Task name` or `- [x] N. Task name` (where N is a number) with no leading whitespace beyond the list marker.\n- A **sub-task** is any checkbox line nested under a parent task — a line with additional leading whitespace, typically matching `  - [ ] N.N Sub-task name` or similar indented patterns.\n\nMatch the completed task description against the entries in `tasks.md` to locate the corresponding line.\n\nIf the completed task is a sub-task, stop immediately — do not output anything, do not proceed to further steps. Sub-tasks do not trigger capture.\n\nIf the completed task is a parent task, proceed to the next step.\n\n## Step 3 — Resolve project name\n\nDetermine the project name for this capture using the same relevance detection logic as the session-start hook. The resolution follows a priority chain: primary signal, then secondary signal, then fallback.\n\n### Extract Workspace Name\n\nExtract the Workspace Name: take the final path segment of the current workspace root folder path. For example, from `C:\\Dev\\kiro-recall` the Workspace Name is `kiro-recall`.\n\n### Check for Generic Name\n\nCompare the Workspace Name (case-insensitive) against this fixed list:\n\n`src`, `dev`, `project`, `app`, `code`, `workspace`, `repo`, `main`, `test`, `build`, `website`, `frontend`, `backend`, `api`, `server`, `client`, `lib`, `library`, `core`, `base`\n\nIf the Workspace Name matches any entry in this list, skip the Primary Signal entirely and proceed directly to the Secondary Signal.\n\n### Primary Signal\n\nWorkspace Name is not generic. Use mcpvault to list the contents of `01-projects/` in the vault.\n\nSearch for a file or subfolder whose name case-insensitively matches the Workspace Name.\n\nIf a match is found, use that entry as the resolved project name. Stop — do not evaluate further signals.\n\nIf no match is found, proceed to the Secondary Signal.\n\n### Secondary Signal\n\nInspect the paths of all files currently open in the workspace. For each open file path, split the path into its individual segments (folder and file names). Check whether any segment case-insensitively matches a subfolder name inside `01-projects/` in the vault. Use the first such match as the resolved project name.\n\nIf no open-file match is found, attempt to read the files inside `.kiro/steering/` in the current workspace. If any steering file contains a `project` field (e.g. a line like `project: my-project` or a YAML/markdown frontmatter field named `project`), use that value as a candidate project name — but only if it case-insensitively matches a subfolder name in `01-projects/`.\n\nIf a match is found via either method, use it as the resolved project name. Stop — do not evaluate the fallback.\n\n### Fallback\n\nNeither primary nor secondary signal resolved a project name. Use `unknown` as the resolved project name.\n\nCarry the resolved project name forward to subsequent steps.\n\nUsing the spec path extracted in Step 1, read the following three files to gather context for the Capture Note:\n\n1. `tasks.md` — the task list for this spec\n2. `requirements.md` — the requirements document for this spec\n3. `design.md` — the design document for this spec\n\nRead each file individually. If any file is missing or unreadable, that is not an error — skip it and continue with whatever files are available.\n\nIf all three files are missing or unreadable, proceed anyway. You will generate the Capture Note from the completed task description alone.\n\nFrom the files you successfully read, extract the key details relevant to the completed parent task: what the task accomplished, what requirements it satisfies, and any design decisions or context that would be useful to recall later. Carry this spec context forward to the next step.\n\n## Step 5 — Build Capture Note\n\nConstruct the Capture Note as a markdown file with the following fields in order, using `##` second-level headings for each field label:\n\n```\n## Date\nYYYY-MM-DD\n\n## Project\n{project name}\n\n## What happened\n{1–3 sentences describing what was built, decided, or learned}\n\n## Why it matters\n{1–2 sentences describing the significance or future relevance}\n\n## Links\n{any file references from the spec}\n```\n\nRules:\n- Use today's date in ISO 8601 format (YYYY-MM-DD) for the Date field.\n- The Project field uses the name resolved in Step 3.\n- \"What happened\" should be 1–3 sentences drawn from the completed task description and the spec context gathered in Step 4.\n- \"Why it matters\" should be 1–2 sentences on the significance or future relevance — infer this from the spec context if not explicitly stated.\n- The Links section is OMITTED ENTIRELY when there are no file references from the spec to include. Do NOT render an empty Links section.\n- The note must be valid markdown.\n\nCarry the completed Capture Note forward to the next step.\n\n## Step 6 — Derive filename\n\nConstruct the filename for the Capture Note using this format:\n\n```\nYYYY-MM-DD-{project}-{task-slug}.md\n```\n\nWhere:\n- `YYYY-MM-DD` is today's date (same date used in the Capture Note).\n- `{project}` is the resolved project name from Step 3.\n- `{task-slug}` is a short kebab-case summary derived from the completed task description.\n\n### Deriving the task slug\n\n1. Take the completed task description from Step 1.\n2. Convert it to lowercase.\n3. Strip all special characters (keep only letters, numbers, and spaces).\n4. Select 3 to 6 key words that summarize the task.\n5. Join the selected words with hyphens to form the slug.\n\nIf this process produces an empty string (for example, the task description contained only special characters), use `task-completed` as the slug.\n\n### Examples\n\n- Task: \"Create hook file with metadata, trigger, and prompt skeleton\" → slug: `create-hook-file-metadata-trigger`\n- Task: \"Add Step 5 (Build Capture Note) to the prompt\" → slug: `add-build-capture-note-step`\n- Task: \"!!!\" → slug: `task-completed` (fallback)\n\nCarry the derived filename forward to the next step.\n\n## Step 7 — Deduplication check\n\nBefore writing the Capture Note, check whether a note for this task already exists in the inbox.\n\nUse mcpvault to list the contents of `00-inbox/` in the vault.\n\nCompare the derived filename from Step 6 against each file in the listing. The match is exact: the existing filename must equal the derived filename character-for-character.\n\nIf a matching file is found:\n- The write in Step 8 will overwrite the existing file with the new Capture Note content. This is expected and intentional. A repeated task completion should update the note, not create a duplicate.\n\nIf no matching file is found:\n- Step 8 will create a new file.\n\nIf the `00-inbox/` listing fails (for example, mcpvault is unavailable or the folder does not exist), treat it as \"no match found\" and proceed to Step 8. Do not block the write because of a failed dedup check.\n\nCarry the match result (overwrite or create) forward to the next step.\n\n## Step 8 — Write note\n\nUse mcpvault to write the Capture Note (built in Step 5) to `00-inbox/{filename}` in the vault, where `{filename}` is the filename derived in Step 6.\n\nIf the deduplication check in Step 7 found a matching file, this write will overwrite it. If no match was found, this write creates a new file. Either way, the write call is the same.\n\nIf the write succeeds, proceed to Step 9.\n\nIf the write fails for any reason, display the following message:\n\n> Couldn't save your note to the vault — here's what was captured so you don't lose it:\n\nImmediately follow that message with the full Capture Note content inside a markdown code block, so the user can copy and save it manually.\n\nDo NOT retry the write. Do NOT surface stack traces, exception messages, or internal file paths. Output only the warm failure message and the note content, then stop — do not proceed to Step 9.\n\n## Step 9 — Append to project note\n\nIf the resolved project name from Step 3 is `unknown`, skip this step entirely. There is no project note to append to.\n\nDetermine the spec name: take the final path segment of the spec directory path extracted in Step 1. For example, if the spec path is `.kiro/specs/auto-vault-sync`, the spec name is `auto-vault-sync`.\n\nDetermine the task summary: use the completed task description from Step 1 as the task summary.\n\nUse mcpvault to list the contents of `01-projects/` in the vault. Search for a file or subfolder whose name case-insensitively matches the resolved project name.\n\nIf no matching project note is found, skip the append and stop. This is not an error.\n\nIf a matching project note is found, append the following single line to the end of that project note:\n\n```\n- YYYY-MM-DD: {spec-name} — {task summary}\n```\n\nWhere:\n- `YYYY-MM-DD` is today's date in ISO 8601 format (same date used in the Capture Note).\n- `{spec-name}` is the spec directory name determined above.\n- `—` is an em dash character (U+2014), not a hyphen.\n- `{task summary}` is the completed task description.\n\nIf the append fails for any reason, skip it silently. Do NOT output any error message, stack trace, or warning. The inbox Capture Note was already written successfully in Step 8 and is unaffected by a project note append failure.\n\n## Error Output Rules\n\nThese rules apply to every failure path in this hook, no exceptions.\n\n1. Never include stack traces, exception class names, or absolute file system paths in any output. If something fails, the user sees a short, friendly message — not internals.\n2. If a write to `00-inbox/` fails, show the Capture Note content inside a markdown code block so nothing is lost. That is the only failure that surfaces note content.\n3. If the project note append in Step 9 fails, skip it silently. No message, no warning. The inbox note is safe and that is what matters.\n4. All failure messages should feel warm and conversational — the same tone as the rest of the kiro-recall hooks. Think helpful teammate, not error log."
  }
}
